<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-partitioned-matrices-complete">
  <title>Module 2: Partitioned Matrices and Matrix Multiplication</title>

  <introduction>
    <objectives>
      <title>Topics and Objectives</title>
      <p>Topics: We will explore the following concepts in this section.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>partitioned matrices (or block matrices)</p></li>
        <li><p>matrix multiplication with partitioned matrices</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>Objectives: After this section, students should be able to apply partitioned matrices to solve problems regarding matrix multiplication.</p>
    </objectives>

    <p><term>Multiple Perspectives</term></p>
    <blockquote cite="William Paul Thurston">
      <p>
        <q>Mathematics is not about numbers, equations, computations, or algorithms. Mathematics is about understanding.</q>
      </p>
      <attribution>William Paul Thurston</attribution>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      Multiple perspectives of the same concept is a theme of this course; each perspective deepens our understanding. In this section, we explore another way of representing matrices and their algebra that gives us another way of thinking about them.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-defining-partitions">
    <title>What is a Partitioned Matrix?</title>
    <p>
      A partitioned matrix is a matrix that has been "sliced" into smaller sub-matrices. For example:
      <me>
        A = \begin{pmatrix} 
        3 \amp 1 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 
        1 \amp 6 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2 
        \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
      can also be written as a block matrix by choosing a specific partition:
      <me>
        A = \left( \begin{array}{ccc|cc}
        3 \amp 1 \amp 4 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        1 \amp 6 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
        \hline
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 2
        \end{array} \right) = \begin{pmatrix} A_{1,1} \amp A_{1,2} \\ A_{2,1} \amp A_{2,2} \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      In this example, we partitioned the matrix into four blocks, each having different dimensions.
    </p>
  </subsection>
  
  

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-utility-and-shorthand">
    <title>Why are Partitioned Matrices Useful?</title>
    <p>
      Partitioned matrices allow for a succinct representation of large, sparse, or structured matrices. For instance, a matrix in row-reduced form often looks like this:
      <me>
        \begin{pmatrix}
        1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp * \amp \dots \amp * \\
        0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp * \amp \dots \amp * \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp * \amp \dots \amp * \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \dots \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \dots \amp 0 
        \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} I_3 \amp F \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      This shorthand is specifically useful when we begin studying the <term>null space</term> of a matrix <m>A</m> later in the semester.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-row-column-method">
    <title>Recall: The Row-Column Method</title>
    <p>
      Recall the standard row-column method for matrix multiplication:
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-row-column-standard">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix and <m>B</m> be an <m>n \times p</m> matrix. Then, the <m>(i, j)</m> entry of <m>AB</m> is the dot product of the <m>i</m>-th row of <m>A</m> and the <m>j</m>-th column of <m>B</m>:
          <me>(AB)_{ij} = \text{row}_i(A) \cdot \text{col}_j(B)</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-row-column-simple">
      <title>Example</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the following product:
          <me>
            AB = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} 
            \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          AB = \begin{pmatrix} (1)(2)+(0)(0)+(1)(0) \amp (1)(-1)+(0)(-1)+(1)(1) \\ (0)(2)+(1)(0)+(1)(0) \amp (0)(-1)+(1)(-1)+(1)(1) \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-block-row-column">
    <title>The Row-Column Method for Block Matrices</title>
    <p>
      Partitioned matrices can be multiplied using this same method, as if each block were a scalar, provided each block has appropriate dimensions so that products are defined.
    </p>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-symbolic-partition">
      <title>Example: Symbolic Block Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Compute the matrix product using the given partitioning:
          <me>
            AB = \left(\begin{array}{cc|c} 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \end{array}\right) 
            \left(\begin{array}{cc} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \\ \hline 0 \amp 1 \end{array}\right) = \begin{pmatrix} I_2 \amp X \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} U \\ Y \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
          Where:
          <me>X = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}, \quad U = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix}, \quad Y = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}</me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Using the row-column method on the blocks:
          <me>AB = (I_2)(U) + (X)(Y)</me>
          <me>
            AB = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
          <me>
            AB = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{pmatrix} + \begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="summary-partitioned-matrices">
    <title>Summary</title>
    <p>
      We explored the following concepts in this video:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Using partitioned matrices to solve problems regarding matrix multiplication.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      *Although not part of our course, matrix partitioning is often used to help derive new algorithms because they give a more concise representation of a matrix and of operations on matrices.*
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>